⚙️ The New Primitive: Relational Equivalence

Symbol (proposal):

≈₍c₎

Read as:

“equivalent under context c”

⸻

Formal idea

a \approx_{c} b

Instead of:
	•	a = b (absolute identity)

We say:
	•	a ≈₍c₎ b (equivalent under some constraint / lens / system)

⸻

🔍 What “c” (context) can be

This is where it gets powerful.

1. Numerical tolerance

a \approx_{\epsilon} b
	•	equal within ε
	•	engineering, physics, real-world math

⸻

2. Transformation equivalence

a \approx_{T} b
	•	a becomes b through transformation T
	•	captures process, not just identity

⸻

3. Structural equivalence

a \approx_{struct} b
	•	same shape, different surface
	•	graphs, systems, patterns

⸻

4. Probabilistic equivalence

a \approx_{p} b
	•	behaves like b with probability p

⸻

5. Perceptual equivalence

a \approx_{obs} b
	•	indistinguishable to an observer

⸻

